tion with the lowest incremental cost.\"", "\"RELEVANT COST OF RAW MATERIALS\":\"A company is evaluating a new contract which requires 400 kg of raw material M. It has 100 kg of material M in inventory which were purchased recently. Since then the purchase price of material M has risen by 4% to $52 per kg. Raw material M is used regularly by the company in normal production. The relevant cost of material M for the contract is calculated based on the replacement cost of $52 per kg, giving a total cost of 400 * 52 = $20,800.\"", "\"RELEVANT COST OF AN IDLE MACHINE\":\"A machine owned by a company has been idle for some months but could now be used on a one-year contract which is under consideration. The net book value of the machine is $1,000. If not used on this contract, the machine could be sold now for a net amount of $1,200. After use on the contract, the machine would have no saleable value and the cost of disposing of it in one year\u2019s time would be $800. The total relevant cost of the machine to the contract is $2,000.\"", "\"MAKE-OR-BUY DECISION COSTS\":\"This quiz question asks about the relevant costs in a make-or-buy decision. The correct answer is the differential costs of both options.\"", "\"PROCESSING FURTHER OR SELLING\":\"Loxwood Co is considering whether to sell its product, the tom, or process it further to make a different product, the tig. It has already incurred processing costs of $3 per unit in relation to the tom. If it sells the tom, it will sell 60,000 units at $8 per unit. Each unit of the tig requires 3 units of the tom and Loxwood Co would expect to sell 20,000 units of the tig. Further variable costs associated with the tig would be $6 per unit and further fixed costs would be $150,000. The selling price of the tig would be $40 per unit. The gain or loss of using the available units of tom to manufacture the tig is a $50,000 profit.\"", "\"DISCONTINUATION OF A PRODUCT TO MAXIMIZE SHORT-TERM PROFIT\":\"Cornaur Products uses a scarce material in the manufacture of four products. Data per unit of each product is shown. In the next period, insufficient material will be available to manufacture all four products and therefore one product must be discontinued. To maximize short-term profit, the product with the lowest contribution per unit of limiting factor, i.e., Product W, should be discontinued.\"", "\"SHADOW PRICE OF MATERIAL\":The \"SHADOW PRICE OF MATERIAL\" is a concept related to Burseldon Co, which manufactures two products, the Cee and the Dee. Information about these products includes details such as selling price, material cost, labor cost, variable overhead, and fixed overhead. The context likely involves calculating the shadow price of material based on the provided data for these products.", "\"SLACK RESOURCES\":\"This quiz involves identifying slack resources for Riley Co, which manufactures two products, eg and pey. The constraints are related to labour and machine time, and the quiz checks if these constraints are fully utilized or if there is slack.\"", "\"PROFIT-MAXIMISING OUTPUT\":\"This quiz involves determining the profit-maximising output of product x for Bruno Co, which manufactures two products, x and y. The constraints are related to materials and labour time, and the solution involves using simultaneous equations.\"", "\"REQUIRED SALES FOR TARGET PROFIT\":\"This quiz involves calculating the number of units Morava Co must sell to generate a target profit. The product has a variable cost and a selling price, and the quiz uses the amended break-even formula for sales volume required to achieve the target profit.\"", "\"BREAKEVEN POINT IN SALES REVENUE\":\"This quiz involves calculating the breakeven point in sales revenue for Dilnot Co, which produces and sells rucksacks and shoulder bags in a standard mix. The quiz uses the contribution to sales ratio and fixed costs to determine the breakeven point.\"", "\"SALES PRICE CALCULATION FOR RUCKSACK\":\"Sales price for Rucksack is calculated as Variable cost / (1 - C/S ratio) = $54 / (1 - 0.4) = $90.\"", "\"SALES PRICE CALCULATION FOR SHOULDER BAG\":\"Sales price for Shoulder bag is calculated as Variable cost / (1 - C/S ratio) = $32.50 / (1 - 0.5) = $65.\"", "\"CONTRIBUTION CALCULATION FOR RUCKSACK\":\"Contribution for Rucksack is calculated as Sales price * C/S ratio = $90 * 0.4 = $36.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}